2025-12-10 20:39:53.311 | WARNING  | agentscope.message.msg:__init__:145 - A new field `role` is newly added to the message. Please specify the role of the message. Currently we use a default "assistant" value.Scientist0: Thought: My motivation stems from the persistent challenge in multi-view stereo (MVS) and single-view depth estimation: accurately reconstructing textureless or low-texture regions where photometric cues are weak or ambiguous. While Paper 2 (SD-MVS) introduces a promising spherical refinement strategy combined with pixelwise depth intervals, its approach treats uncertainty in a somewhat implicit manner—relying on EM optimization to tune hyperparameters but not explicitly modeling geometric uncertainty during perturbation. Additionally, spherical coordinate perturbation is powerful for normal refinement, but without a principled way to quantify confidence in the direction of perturbation, it risks overfitting to noise or converging to incorrect local minima in flat regions.

I aim to improve upon this by introducing an *uncertainty-aware* mechanism that dynamically modulates the magnitude and direction of spherical perturbations based on per-pixel geometric confidence. This confidence is derived from both the consistency of depth intervals across views and the local surface entropy estimated via learned geodesic-like smoothness priors—inspired by the lifted space concept in Paper 1, though not directly using geodesics. Furthermore, instead of fixed or empirically tuned search ranges, I propose adaptive depth interval scaling governed by epipolar uncertainty and semantic edge coherence (leveraging SAM as in SD-MVS, but repurposed for boundary-aware regularization).

This idea diverges from prior work in three key ways: (1) It explicitly models directional uncertainty in spherical perturbation, making refinement robust rather than heuristic; (2) It integrates depth interval dynamics with normal evolution through a joint probabilistic framework, enabling bidirectional feedback between depth and normal estimates; and (3) It uses semantic edges not just for segmentation-driven deformation, but as geometric priors to constrain smoothing across boundaries, preserving sharp features in textureless zones like white walls or metallic surfaces.

The result is a more principled, self-correcting refinement loop that reduces drift in uniform areas while enhancing detail at object silhouettes and creases—addressing a core limitation in current MVS pipelines.

